2026-03-23 — Race Engineer Mode
==================================

THE INSIGHT

Everyone optimizes training. TTT is the underfloor.

  Training innovations (100+ PRs):  1.224 -> 1.118 = -0.106 BPB
  TTT alone:                        1.118 -> 0.997 = -0.121 BPB

TTT is worth more than all architecture work combined.
But architecture determines HOW MUCH TTT helps:

  Standard arch + AdamW TTT:  -0.019 BPB
  PR #462 arch + AdamW TTT:  -0.053 BPB  (2.8x amplification)
  PROTEUS + LoRA TTT:        -0.121 BPB  (architecture designed for it)

Newey found downforce in the underfloor while everyone polished
the bodywork. We find BPB in the eval budget while everyone
polishes the training loop.

DEPENDENCY GRAPH

BPB = prediction_quality × tokenizer_efficiency  (MULTIPLICATIVE)

prediction_quality
├── model_knowledge (weights after training)
│   ├── architecture_efficiency ← FREE VARIABLE (highest leverage)
│   ├── tokens_seen = 600s / step_latency × batch_tokens
│   │   └── step_latency ← DERIVED from architecture + hardware bandwidth
│   ├── learning_per_token ← near-optimal (Muon, 100+ PRs)
│   └── loss_function ← UNDEREXPLORED (everyone uses standard CE)
├── quant_gap ← DERIVED from architecture's weight distribution
└── eval_adaptation
    ├── TTT_delta ← DERIVED from architecture's loss landscape geometry
    ├── neural_cache (non-parametric, zero grad, stacks with TTT)
    └── stride-OGD (already implemented)

tokenizer_efficiency ← FREE VARIABLE (sp4096 = 1.35× multiplier)

Architecture is the single free variable that feeds the MOST derived
variables: raw capacity, quant gap, TTT delta, step latency, artifact
size. This is why architecture search is highest leverage.

NOVEL INTERVENTIONS (each attacks a different node)

1. Multi-Token Prediction (loss_function node)
   Train with 2 heads: predict t+1 AND t+2. Discard head 2 at eval.
   Zero artifact cost. <5% training overhead. Better representations.
   Forces backbone to encode structure, not just local patterns.
   ~20 lines of code. Free lunch.

2. Depth Recurrence (architecture_efficiency node)
   Store 6 blocks, loop 2x = 12 effective layers.
   Reinvest savings: 640d + MLP 4x. Per-loop LoRA for specialization.
   PR #499 "Frugendorff" validates at 1.1478 BPB (no TTT!).
   TTT compound: adapting 6 shared blocks = 2x leverage per param
   (each adapted weight used twice in forward pass).

3. Neural Cache (eval_adaptation node, orthogonal to TTT)
   Cache (hidden_state, next_token) during eval. Similarity lookup.
   p(y|x) = (1-λ)*p_model + λ*p_cache
   Zero params, zero gradients, captures local repetition.
   Literature: ~10% perplexity gain. Stacks with TTT.

4. Online TTT / Dynamic Eval (eval_adaptation node)
   Adapt per-window during sliding eval. Single-pass, causal.
   DeepMind 2024: middle layers most effective to adapt.
   Different from batch TTT — more document-specific.

DEAD ENDS (researched, ruled out)
- SAM: 2x compute overhead, disqualifying in 10-min race.
  EMA/SWA gets similar flat-minima benefits for free.
- kNN-LM: 400GB datastore. Completely infeasible for 16MB artifact.
- Full MTP beyond k=2: diminishing returns, not worth overhead.

MOVES

1. Get AdamW TTT into train_gpt.py. Can't race without an engine.
2. Add MTP (k=2) to training. Free lunch, ~20 lines.
3. GEPA-style search on L40S ($0.26/hr). Metric = TTT DELTA.
   Search space includes depth recurrence as an architecture axis.
4. sp4096 x winner compound. 1.35x multiplier on all gains.
5. Add neural cache to eval pipeline. Stacks with TTT for free.
6. Final 8xH100 submission with winning recipe.

RULES

- L40S is for architecture families ONLY
- Never tune LR, warmdown, batch, momentum on proxy
- Primary metric: adaptation_uplift = BPB_no_ttt - BPB_after_ttt
- Rich diagnostics, not scalar scores
- Reflect after each wave, mutate directed

HARDWARE

L40S secure spot, RunPod: $0.26/hr
  6L compiled SDPA: ~306ms/step, ~1960 steps/10min
  11L compiled SDPA: ~585ms/step, ~1025 steps/10min
  Fixed 1500 steps per run (~$0.06-0.09 each)
  No FA3 (Hopper only). No DDP (single GPU). SDPA + compile.

DIAGNOSTICS

Every run logs:
  quant_gap_by_block   — int6 each block solo, measure loss delta
  activation_outliers  — max/mean/std per layer (attn logits + MLP hidden)
  weight_effective_rank — SVD per weight matrix, rank at 90% variance
  adaptation_uplift    — BPB delta from 10ep AdamW TTT
  lora_sensitivity     — SVD proxy: how much can rank-8 capture?
  artifact_bytes       — estimated int6+zstd size
  loss_curve_slope     — final 100 steps trend (descending vs plateau)
  step_time_ms         — sanity only, never optimize for this

EXPERIMENT WAVES

Config shared across all runs:
  TRAIN_BATCH_TOKENS=131072
  TRAIN_SEQ_LEN=1024
  ITERATIONS=1500
  MAX_WALLCLOCK_SECONDS=0
  VAL_TOKENS_LIMIT=1048576
  WARMUP_STEPS=2
  SDPA (no FA3), single GPU, torch.compile

--- Wave 1: Calibrate (4 runs, ~$0.30) ---

Establish baselines. Answer: what's our TTT delta? Does sp4096 amplify it?

  A: 11L sp1024 baseline         -> raw BPB + diagnostics
  B: 11L sp1024 + TTT 10ep       -> TTT delta (this is our reference)
  C: 11L sp4096 baseline         -> raw BPB + diagnostics
  D: 11L sp4096 + TTT 10ep       -> TTT delta (compare to B)

Decision gate: if sp4096 TTT delta > sp1024, lock in sp4096 for later waves.

--- Wave 2: Architecture families (8 runs, ~$0.65) ---

All sp1024 (controlled). Vary one architecture axis per run.
Every run includes MTP k=2 (free lunch, always on after Wave 1).
Measure adaptation_uplift + full diagnostics for each.

  E: 11L + SwiGLU (replace relu^2)
  F: 11L + learned sigmoid gating on U-Net skips
  G: 11L + Value Residual (cache V from layer 0, blend all layers)
  H: 11L + SwiGLU + learned gating combined (PR #462 recipe)
  I: 11L + Gated Attention (per-head sigmoid gate)
  J: 6Lx2 recurrence, 640d, MLP 4x, per-loop LoRA (Frugendorff-style)
  K: 6Lx2 recurrence + SwiGLU
  L: 6Lx2 recurrence + SwiGLU + learned gating

Rank all by adaptation_uplift. The winner isn't the best raw BPB.
It's the biggest TTT delta.
The recurrence runs (J-L) test the 2x TTT leverage hypothesis.

--- Wave 3: Compound (3-4 runs, ~$0.30) ---

Combine top-2 amplifiers from Wave 2.
Use diagnostics reflection to guide combos:
  - if both amplifiers are quant-friendly (low outliers), combine
  - if one has high effective rank + one has low, they may complement
  - test 2-3 combos of winners

--- Wave 4: sp4096 x winner (2-3 runs, ~$0.20) ---

Apply winning architecture family to sp4096 tokenizer.
Measure compound: does tokenizer multiplier stack with arch amplifier?
If yes, this is our submission recipe.

--- Wave 5: Eval stack (2-3 runs, ~$0.20) ---

On winning architecture from Wave 3/4:
  M: +neural cache (interpolation weight λ sweep: 0.05, 0.1, 0.2)
  N: +online TTT per-window (middle layers only, per DeepMind 2024)
  O: neural cache + batch TTT together (do they stack?)

--- Wave 6: 8xH100 (1-2 runs, ~$7) ---

Full 10-min train. Real batch (786K), real FA3, real DDP.
Tune warmdown/LR HERE, not before.
Full eval stack: LoRA TTT + neural cache + stride-OGD.

Total: ~$6 research + ~$7 submission = ~$13

TTT RECIPE (from PR #462, our starting point)

  optimizer: AdamW(all_params, lr=5e-4, wd=0.0)
  scheduler: CosineAnnealingLR(T_max=10, eta_min=5e-5)
  epochs: 10
  grad_clip: 1.0
  batch: 32 sequences x 1024 tokens
  data: full validation set, sequential chunks
  when: after EMA (if used), before quantization
  measure: sliding window BPB before and after

GEPA LOOP (manual, Claude as reflection LM)

  1. SELECT: pick architecture variant from plan or Pareto front
  2. EXECUTE: run on L40S, collect full diagnostics
  3. REFLECT: Claude reads diagnostics, diagnoses WHY
     - "loss plateau + high activation outliers = quant-unfriendly"
     - "low TTT delta + high effective rank = already well-fit, no room to adapt"
     - "big TTT delta + steep loss curve = undertrained, adaptation fills gaps"
  4. MUTATE: propose next variant based on diagnosis, not random
  5. ACCEPT: if TTT delta improves, add to frontier

Each cycle: one L40S run (~15 min) + 5 min analysis = 20 min.
3 cycles/hr. 15 cycles in an afternoon = $2.

THE NOVEL STACK (our bet)

  depth recurrence (6x2) + MTP (k=2) + sp4096 + AdamW TTT + neural cache

Each component attacks a different node in the dependency graph.
They don't compete — they compound:
  recurrence → artifact-efficient depth + 2x TTT leverage
  MTP → better representations → smoother landscape → more TTT gain
  sp4096 → 1.35x multiplier on every per-token improvement
  TTT → eval-time adaptation (amplified by recurrence)
  neural cache → non-parametric local patterns (stacks with TTT)

Nobody has combined these. This is our differentiated play.

PARAMETRIC VS NON-PARAMETRIC MEMORY

Model = 15M params × ~2.6 bits (int6) ≈ 40M bits of storage.
FineWeb val = ~620M bits of entropy. Model is 15x too small to memorize.
It MUST generalize.

TTT = parametric memorization (gradient-based, lossy, into weights).
Neural cache = non-parametric memorization (exact lookup, local, zero cost).
Stride-OGD = lightweight parametric (vocab bias vector only).
These address different failure modes and stack additively.

THINGS TO REMEMBER

- We're not forking PROTEUS or PR #462. We're finding our own underfloor.
- sp4096 is our unique angle. Nobody else has submitted it + TTT.
- The architecture that trains best is NOT the architecture that adapts best.
- Flat minima = good TTT. EMA/SWA for free, SwiGLU and learned gating help.
- Depth recurrence: PR #499 validates at 1.1478 BPB. TTT on shared
  weights is 2x leverage — completely unexplored compound.
- MTP k=2: zero artifact cost, <5% overhead, better representations.
  Always-on after validation. Free lunch.
- Neural cache: zero params, zero grads, ~10% perplexity in literature.
  Captures exactly what the model can't: local repetition patterns.
- MAML is high-risk: only after Waves 1-4 validate the direction.
